ğŸ° Interesting fact: Nosferatu (2024) â€” In Robert Eggersâ€™ recent reimagining of the 1922 classic, Bill SkarsgÃ¥rd spent six hours in the makeup chair every day to transform into Count Orlok. SkarsgÃ¥rd worked with a movement coach to develop an â€œinhumanâ€ way of walking and standing that defied normal skeletal structure, making the vampire feel like a literal walking corpse. Samay Raina is a well-known stand-up comedian in India who has built a large following for his unique humor, wit, and relatability. Originally from Jammu, Samay started his career in comedy in his college days and quickly rose to prominence, becoming one of the youngest comedians to gain significant traction in the Indian stand-up scene. Known for his sharp observational comedy, he touches upon topics ranging from Indian family dynamics and cultural quirks to current events and internet trends, all delivered with a relatable, down-to-earth style that resonates with audiences across India. In addition to stand-up, Samay Raina is widely recognized for his popular live streaming and content creation, particularly around chess. During the COVID-19 pandemic, he introduced a wider audienceto the game of chess by collaborating with top Indian chess grandmasters and streaming entertaining chess matches, where he combined humor with chess commentary. This initiative contributed significantly to popularizing online chess in India and has drawn a younger audience to the game. Jaguars have surprisingly long, striking eyelashes that serve a purpose far beyond looks. These thick lashes help shield their eyes from dust, debris, and small insects as they move through dense forests or dry, dusty habitats. By limiting the amount of particles that reach the eyes, their eyelashes help keep their vision clear, which is crucial for a predator that depends on sharp eyesight to hunt with precision. Can she level up and gain hearts back tho?? Renaming contacts with emojis has become a pretty common thing, especially hearts in romantic or close relationships. Psychologists actually link this kind of behavior to gamification, where people turn emotional situations into simple visual systems to feel more control over them. Using symbols instead of names can make emotions feel more concrete, like progress bars or lives in a game, even though nothing actually changes in real life. That idea lines up with how people already treat phones as emotional tools, not just communication ones. Studies on digital habits show people often use contact names, notes, and emojis to cope with stress, set boundaries, or mark relationship shifts without having to say them out loud. Itâ€™s basically modern relationship bookkeeping, just done through a screen instead of a conversation.

It grew the way shadows grow in the evening, slowly, faithfully, without asking permission. Whether you are ready or not, it is once again #UshyGushyMushy season. I couldnâ€™t let November go by without reminding you all of the fantastically moist mushrooms that can be found in the forest this time of year. . Here I pay tribute to the multitude of impressively goopy jelly fungi and wet pileuses! Most of these gelatinous growths belong to the Tremellaceae family, which are evolutionarily ancient mushrooms that occur on decaying wood. The ecology of these fungi is fascinating as they are actually parasitizing the mycelium of other species in the wood (as opposed to rotting the wood itself) and in their asexual/haploid state they can exist as single celled yeasts capable of causing disease in humans. The jellies that grow on conifers are in Dacrymycetaceae, which are pure saprotrophs rather than parasitic. . As always, I recognize this content can be polarizing. Itâ€™s so interesting to me how these videos elicit reactions that span the full gamut of human emotion; from revulsion to adoration, outrage to amusement, feeling skeeved out to weirdly turned on. Some people love the squishy squelchy noises while others find them revolting or downright disgusting. Regardless of what you feel, these videos have garnered millions of views worldwide while transcending languages and cultural backgrounds - demonstrating that humans everywhere feel a deep connection with ushy gushy fungi. . Content like this is part of my educational strategy to expose people to mushrooms, this video is intended to be emotionally evocative. I am demonstrating that mushrooms are safe to touch and handle. Humans have been anthropomorphizing mushrooms for millennia, Iâ€™m not doing anything new here (calm down Karen). No disrespect intended, I love nature. Please keep the feedback civil and be kind to each other - the world is difficult enough as it is. . Keep the projections and personal judgements to a minimum, this is art. Credit @s.e.jal - Fish are the most diverse group of vertebrates (animals with backbones) on the planet, with an estimated 34,000 different known species. Unlike land animals, most fish have a specialized internal organ called the swim bladder which they fill with gas to control their buoyancy, allowing them to maintain their position at different depths in the water column without sinking or floating up. A surprising fact about their senses is that fish generally do not have eyelids (sharks are an exception) and therefore cannot close their eyes! They also have a unique sensory organ called the lateral line, a system of tiny, fluid-filled canals running along the sides of their bodies. This â€œsixth senseâ€ acts like a built-in radar, detecting vibrations, pressure changes, and movements in the water around them, helping them navigate and school.
